Love yourself every single day. In moments of insecurity, remind yourself that you are capable because you are, you really are.
Don't compare your life to others. There's no comparison between the sun and the moon, they shine when it's their time.
What a wonderful thought it is that some of the best days of our lives haven't happened yet.
You are strong enough to face it all, even if it doesn't feel like it right now.
There are 3 things you are always in total control over: your attitude, your choices, and your effort.
This is just the beginning. And it's only going to get better from here.
If you feel like you're losing everything, remember that trees lose their leaves every year and they still stand tall and wait for better days to come.
People show their true colors unintentionally. Pay attention.
You're busy doubting yourself while some people are intimidated by your potential.
The happiness of your life depends on the quality of your thoughts.
You are loved no matter how you feel.
Your life only gets better when you do. Work on yourself and the rest will follow.
Be obsessed with your own potential.
If you don't like where you are, MOVE. You are not a tree.
Forgive yourself for all the mistakes you think you've made.
Train your mind to see the good in everything. Positivity is a choice. The happiness of your life depends on the quality of your thoughts.
Don't wish for it. Work for it.
You are the artist of your own life. Don't hand the paintbrush to anyone else.
Expect nothing. Appreciate everything.
Life always offers you a second chance. It's called tomorrow.
Become the hardest working person you know.
If it makes you happy, no one else's opinion should matter.
One small positive thought in the morning can change your whole day.
Your potential to succeed is infinite.
Good things take time.
Stop trying to calm the storm. Calm yourself. The storm will pass.
You are the most valuable investment you will ever make.
Push yourself, because no one else is going to do it for you.
Staying positive doesn't mean you have to be happy all the time. It means that even on hard days you know that there are better ones coming.
Sometimes when things are falling apart they may actually be falling into place.
Be yourself. People don't have to like you, and you don't have to care.
It's a good day to have a good day.
Your mind is a powerful thing. When you fill it with positive thoughts, your life will start to change.
Believe in yourself and you will be unstoppable.
Put on your positive pants.
Your life doesn't get better by chance. It gets better by change.
Scared? Good. We don't grow when we stay inside our comfort zone.
You don't need to have all the answers to start. You just have to be willing to take the first step.
A beautiful day begins with a beautiful mindset.
Focus on the good.
When you feel like quitting, think about why you started.
Look for something positive in each day, even if some days you have to look a little harder.
Be so happy that when others look at you, they become happy too!
In a world where you can be anything, be kind.
Spend time with people who bring out the best in you, not the stress in you.
Your life is as good as your mindset.
A negative mind will never give you a positive life.
Be addicted to bettering yourself.
Personal growth often comes from discomfort, pain, and challenges.
Get into the habit of asking yourself "Does this support the life I'm trying to create?"
Learn to see rejection as redirection.
Feel the fear and do it anyway.
Don't take criticism from people you would never go to for advice.
Use the 21/90 rule. It takes 21 days to build a habit, and 90 days to build a lifestyle.
Make your happiness and personal growth a priority in your life. The more you take care of yourself, the more you can take care of others.
Only you can turn your dreams into a reality. And you have everything you need to make it happen.
Stop overthinking things and just do it.
You don't have to be extreme. Just consistent.
Every day is a new opportunity to change your life.
Just because it is hard doesn't mean it's impossible. You can do it.
If you don't like something, remember you have the power to change it.
The struggle is part of the journey. Everyone goes through it. Keep going and don't give up.
Get out of your own way.
If it doesn't challenge you, it won't change you.
Always go with the choice that scares you the most, because that's the one that is going to help you grow.
Take a moment to appreciate how far you have come.

Deep down you know exactly what you are capable of. There are even moments where you get a glimpse of all the potential you have. You can get there. You just have to be willing to sacrifice the habits, things, and situations that are standing in the way of your success.
You don't need someone else's permission to live your own life.
First you dream, then you do.
Stop worrying if other people will like you. Do you like yourself?
There's someone out there who needs to hear your story from you.
Keep going. You did not come this far just to come this far.
Act like the person you want to become.
Life gets better when you stop waiting for other people to love you and decide to start loving yourself.
Your life is not permanent. You are not stuck. You have choices. You are allowed to grow and change.
We're not meant to stay the same. Change is good.
Work on you. For you.
Stop calling it your dream. Start calling it your plan.
You are not going to master the rest of your life in one day. Just relax. Master the day. Then just keep going that every day.
Never underestimate the investment you make in yourself.
When you are confident, people become confident in you.
Nothing changes if nothing changes.
If you focus on the hurt, you will continue to suffer. If you focus on the lesson, you will continue to grow.
Always deliver more than expected.
Your life isn't yours if you always care what others think.
Allow yourself to grow and change. Your future self is waiting.
Remember, if you play small, you stay small. It's okay to want more, do more, be more.
Stop shrinking to fit into places you've outgrown.
You can handle whatever life throws at you.
When things change inside of you, things change around you.
You can literally create your dream life if you believe in yourself and show up every day to do the work.
It's not enough to just start. You have to keep going too.
Having the right mindset and attitude can literally change your life.
When you focus on the good, the good gets better.
Growth is often uncomfortable, messy, and full of feelings you weren't expecting, but it's necessary.
Where you are a year from now is a reflection of the choices you choose to make right now.
Every single thing that has happened in your life is preparing you for a moment that is yet to come.
You're gonna make it.
Limits only exist in the mind.
I am ready for the next level in my personal evolution.

"No elections or debates, options and oppositions dont exist, there is no popular will in NGOs or international organizations: what they have is cash and lobby. No peoples, only a sickening mix of bureaucrats, philanthropists, millionaires, and celebrity figureheads." #NewRight

"NGOs, for their part, do not have democratic legitimacy either: their legitimacy is a function of how much propaganda they enjoy, how many media favors they receive, how many celebrities weigh in, and all this can boil down to the size of their annual budget." #NewRight

"Thus, these structures are filled with all kinds of 'experts', on all kind of topics: gender, childhood, economics, environmental, human rights, women's rights, race, ethnicity, governance, etc." #NewRight

"Globalist power is technocratic and elitist. It is some sort of 'enlightened despotism': the legitimacy of international organizations does not really rest on democratic mechanisms, but on the 'expert' status of its occupants." #NewRight

"Political power is increasingly being placed in international organizations that, while adding initials and functions, weave a complex web of power which defies the sovereignty and autonomy of Nation-States." #NewRight

"Alain de Benoist was correct when he wrote that 'today it is inconvenient, blasphemous, and scandalous to criticize human rights ideology, just as it was earlier to doubt the existence of God.'" #NewRight
"Human rights have plenty of political religion in them; like God, and State, they are written with initial capital letters." #NewRight

"But, as opposed to it, this law does not stem from a tradition of transmitted (and limited) Revelations, but from revelations from those who have global political power to decide what is a Human Right, today, here and now, one way today, another way tomorrow." #NewRight
"Like Christianity, it appeals to a universal conception that humanity is reconciled in compliance with a single Law, the true law." #NewRight

"Just as with natural law, the new doctrine seeks, in principle, to protect the individual from the State; but, unlike the aforementioned law, it creates a potentially more powerful bureaucracy." #NewRight

"During the 19th century, international law was conceived as a structure from which it was possible to regulate relationships between States. In the 20th century, the doctrine of human rights would be born, including the individual as the subject of international law." #NewRight
"International law, as it refers to its development and expansion, precisely reflects the actual crisis of the Nation-State." #NewRight

"International and regional bureaucracies are being gradually imposed on the national ones; and their regulations, often removed from all effective citizen power, steamroll the cracked framework of national law." #NewRight

"In other words, the State, in a state of permanent expansion, has experienced however a relative decrease in power, insofar as the political power of international organizations has been growing." #NewRight

"This loss is not of political power as in a fall in the total amount; quite the opposite: the State is being overtaken by the urgency of a superior power, that has started regimenting States (and therefore societies) through international organizational structures." #NewRight
"In addition to the nation, the State is currently losing two essential elements: autonomy and sovereignty." #NewRight

"Thus, the State begins experiencing a process of not only the annihilation of the centralization of the political space, but also the eradication of the State's defining cultural component: the nation." #NewRight

"This is so because the near and the distant, a game of differences that structures national cultures, is itself a dichotomy that loses meaning in a world where the entire globe's interactivity is mediated by one click, satellites, and optic fiber." #NewRight
"For a start, in a framework in which global interactions become part of the everyday experience, the national/foreign dichotomy loses clarity." #NewRight
"In the last few decades, State-level changes have been truly significant." #NewRight

"However, no one who does not want to endanger his own reputation should subject to deconstruction the deepest values and beliefs of the migrants that arrive to western nations in search of prosperity and security." #NewRight

"The postmodern frame of mind, however, is not applied evenly: the deconstruction of the nation and its cultural particularities becomes categorically imperative when it comes to a western nation." #NewRight
"The nations' outlines are fading due to material reasons like mass migrations, but also due to ideological reasons like the deliberate attack on the national sentiment." #NewRight

"Nationalism, on the other hand, is a political and cultural project that highlights the primacy of these affinities, and the necessity to spread them out on a territory in coincidence with its sovereign." #NewRight
"The modern State goes hand in hand with a nation as a collective entity defined by profound historic, linguistic, symbolic and projective affinities." #NewRight

"The politician who, in the past, had to wait his turn to appear in front of the small screen and to become a "personality" similar to show business celebrities, now makes a permanent reality show on social media out of his own life." #NewRight

"If public opinion  is what transpires from the interactions that arise in the public space; on TV there is no public opinion, but rather the opinion that is published by the elite of the screen." #NewRight
"Postmodern culture is the culture of the difference: it exalts the anomaly, the deviation, the extravagant." #NewRight

"Repetition generates majorities; differences generate minorities. On TV, the repetitive is tiring: it calls for changing the channel. Women who are women and men who are men, like any other, is tiring." #NewRight

"Just as the weather girls, who don't know much about climatology, but have spent many hours working out glutes, celebrities do not often know much about anything, but they have appeared on TV for hours. For TV, you need to be likable, not convincing." #NewRight
"These women are more important than the weather, just like today's celebrities are more important than the bland surveys carefully and methodologically proposed by the social sciences." #NewRight
"Nonetheless, these numbers prove to be a bit boring. Just like the weather report, for which beautiful women, made up of gym and silicon, are needed." #NewRight

"In the past, the fathers of modern democracy made efforts for articulated reason to be seen as "general will"; today, only opinion surveys, preference polls, and hunches-turned-figures on screen remain. Bar graphs, points, and pie charts can be televised." #NewRight
"It is no coincidence that the verb "to feel" is most widely used today than the verb "to think" ("I feel that...": this is how "arguments" are presented today)." #NewRight

"The era of reason, typically modern and enlightened, has been replaced by the era of opinion, typically postmodern. The former is "solid", the latter is "liquid". The first is "episteme", the second is pure "doxa": a hunch that doesn't really need an argument." #NewRight
"Video-democracy corresponds to video-politics. If the politician becomes a celebrity, the people become spectators. The activist model yields to the emergence of the fan." #NewRight
"What does a politician represent today but the cultural simulation that conceals the most pathetic nothingness on which politics rests today?" #NewRight

"...what his perfect fur dog barks, what his countless anecdotes, jokes, and unsubstantiated but nice-sounding declarations on countless TV hours during primetime throws on millions of people?" #NewRight

"With that in mind, cultural demand is followed by cultural supply. What does a politician represent today but what his slogans promise, what his catchy jingles sing, what his family picture evokes, what his video with the idol or star of the moment insinuates,..." #NewRight

"But today, political power can only be placed below, undergoing imperatives, and technical and media working rules, neither issued nor chosen by it. Only by becoming totalitarian, it can intend to get hold of total cultural control, with debatable success probability." #NewRight

"Political power created crests, seals, portraits, banners, hymns, schools, institutions, and it gave the people representatives and laws, positioning itself above the cultural power, under which it secured its own legitimacy." #NewRight

"The culture war not only makes sense, but it also becomes central, inevitable, omnipresent, and it confused itself with every struggle for power: there wont be a power struggle (political, economic, military, etc) that does not develop its own culture war." #NewRight
"What happens when the people is more interested in voting for a reality show character (even paying for it on their smartphone) than for their political representative?" #NewRight

"Political power has always wanted cultural power (it always needed to legitimize the use of force with something different than itself), but as modernity wanted to distinguish both spheres, today they mix incessantly." #NewRight

"The political indignation that could sprout from the received "information" is turned into distraction. To be politically informed is not substantially different than being informed about the latest show business events or its gossips." #NewRight

"Thus, political but "entertaining" programs are demanded. With laugh tracks, embedded sounds, jokes, screams, and previously scripted postures. Celebrities are always invited to share their "opinions", as if they had any real value." #NewRight
"On television, everything is framed as entertainment, and it is very difficult to escape this logic. Even for politics it proves to be almost impossible." #NewRight

"Thus, a political-military failure became a political-cultural victory thanks to the small screen. Revolutions shall be mediated or they will not be; revolutions, consequently, shall largely be cultural or they will not be." #NewRight

"Or how the "Bolivarian Revolution" did not have its true starting point with Hugo Chavez's failed coup in 1992, but with his later appearance on television, that he negotiated during his military surrender." #NewRight

"Where is the revolution, then? In the great television studios. One would now have to remember, for example, the Romanian uprising of 1989, when the demonstrators took over the TV stations. It was not a random act, but a strategic one." #NewRight
"Politics has never been as dominated by the low-calorie culture." #NewRight

"A media revolution that displaced the center of politics separates us between Lincoln's debates and Kennedy's make-up: from word to image, from logos to pathos, from content to form, from systematic ideologies (or "great narratives") to weak thoughts." #NewRight
"And the most important thing in this hegemonic consolidation is that we have lost sight of this: its ability to make us see everything." #NewRight

"Its power to appropriate what is real is unlimited: cameras are not a thing of actors and hosts, but also of police officers, criminals, physicians, drug addicts, politicians, militaries..." #NewRight
"No record of life exists that does not fit actually or potentially on television; no area of life exists that can not be transformed in cultural simulation." #NewRight
"... deep ocean exploration, moon exploration, jungle exploration and human exploration, cooking, music, fashion, sports, and an endless etcetera." #NewRight

"Everything can become a televised spectacle: war, politics, economics, history, news, sexuality, tourism, the life of celebrities, the life of non-celebrities who want to be celebrities, health, sickness, vices, virtues, crime, religion, science, the party,..." #NewRight

"But the hegemony of television does not amount to mere domination over all other media, but also over the lives of the masses to an unknown level. Thus, everything is redirected towards television; everything fits. #NewRight
"One of the most crucial differences is that television, unlike cinema, is capable of subsuming any type of discourse, becoming a sort of meta-medium." #NewRight

"Said differently, what we see on screen seems too real to be mediated; thus, it appears immediate. Such is the most powerful effect of television: the power to conceal its own mediation effects." #NewRight

""It was shown on television" is a way of asserting a "truth" as self-evident, irrefutable: this is possible because the medium of television renders self-evident that which recieves media coverage, because it provides a reality that does not seem mediated." #NewRight

"Television, by contrast, simultaneously, places image and sound in our reach, jointly, and uninterruptedly, for the most part all day long and every day of the year: it is a relentless representation of reality that passes for reality." #NewRight

"Said differently, representation via words involves man in the rebuilding process of the message and its reality, which is by no means sufficient with just the sound that emerges from radio (or letters in text), but requires further significant involvement." #NewRight
"An extra effort is always demanded from man; the medium accompanies, it creates the symbolic conditions from which the individual actively concludes the suggested representation." #NewRight

"Not just with text, but also with sound, man must "complete", so to speak, a reality significantly incomplete, by imagining or abstracting. Neither text nor radio can colonize reality: they do not have the technological means to do it." #NewRight

"Television defeated the letters, but it also defeated radio. Neither are capable of creating a separate world in which our world flows. The reason for that is that both media inevitably appeal to the imagination, and imagination involves the receiver directly." #NewRight

"... the Dynamic Cognition Laboratory at Washington University, using brain scanners, highlighted how reading stimulates the brain: "readers mentally simulate every new situation that they find in a story"." #NewRight

"...Marco Ennemoser and Wolfgang Schneider, from the University of Wurzburg, found that the greater the exposure of children to television, the lesser the vocabulary development; invertedly, with more reading, vocabulary was richer and diverse." #NewRight

"But, on television, time is subjected to planned programming and guidelines that shreds it, and crushes it to a level where interventions of argumentative discourse cannot extend more than a few seconds, which hampers any truly argumentative record of the discourse." #NewRight
"Critical thought is sluggish; it needs to pause itself, to advance slowly, to step back and then advance again, going in circles a few times." #NewRight

"The capacity to think conceptually, which develops itself mainly from reading, is being lost; the cultural dominance of the screen requires the individual's capacity to watch, not really think." #NewRight

"Homo Sapiens, the man who thinks using symbols and abstractions, is being replaced by a self-degraded version, Homo Videns who, according to Sartori, simply reduces his own reality spectrum to that which can be represented by an image." #NewRight

"Man has gone from a word based culture to an image based culture. This inspired interesting critiques like Postman's or Sartori's. Because, unlike reading printed text, the activity of looking at the screen does not produce the same cognitive effort of abstraction." #NewRight
"Cinema offers something akin to reality that, however, is nothing more than the technical rebuilding of carefully prepared fragments." #NewRight

"Cinema, for its part, will take another step, committing itself to movement, which is by definition elusive to photography: what cinema shows is not an instant, but a succession (of photograms)." #NewRight
"Photography, unlike painting, claims an absolute fidelity with respect to what it shows: a precise copy, virtually capable of capturing what it is as it is. Principle of cloning." #NewRight

"The cultural element known as the image was never so important to power and to politics as in post-modernism, where politics and culture confuse themselves increasingly and where, consequently, the culture war becomes permanent." #NewRight
"...they don't represent the real, not even produce alternative realities, but rather they erect themselves as a point of reference in which the real must assimilate itself." #NewRight

"Even so, it could be said that, in the world of the image, the images precede their references: they are the cause and not the effect. In such a circumstance, the images become the reference of the real;..." #NewRight

"In a sense, more than a facade, the image today is a simulation. Therefore, fleeing the world of the image is not as simple as fleeing Plato's Cave. To escape from the appearances of the shadows is not the same as escaping from the empire of the image." #NewRight

"The camera, in the world of images, is a technological messiah that guarantees the ontological salvation of what it appropriates as image; the image is the consecration of the thing. The image is a facade." #NewRight

"It is difficult to imagine a culture devoid of images. Paleolithic men painted their caverns for magical purposes. Ancient cultures, like the Sumerian or the Egyptian, among others, have left numerous examples of this that are displayed in the great museums of today." #NewRight
"What is at the center of this is not a change in economic variables, but above all, a political-cultural change; and such change is not spontaneous, but active, sought, and militated." #NewRight

"Today's so-called "cancel culture" takes products out of the market not because they have no demand, but because they expose the company to cultural smears actively promoted by radicalized cultural movements." #NewRight

"The market was delighted with feminism because it could sell it, and by selling it, it enabled and reinforced its cultural hegemony. This became so decisive in political terms that politics reacted against the market using the weapons the market helped loading." #NewRight

"In fact, hegemony is implacable to state coercion, as Gramsci noted. In non-totalitarian systems, the market  emerges as a mechanism for the massive circulation of the elements of a culture war." #NewRight
"... it is difficult for culture wars to avoid the massive benefits of the economic mechanisms." #NewRight

"That said, as culture wars seek to control, not in isolation but in a hegemonic fashion, and because hegemony, by definition, demands for a quantitative extension of control (something that's hegemonic is something that is imposed on and is accepted by the masses),..." #NewRight
"In an armed conflict, weaponry has control over life and death; in a culture war, the cultural ammunition has control over the image of life and death." #NewRight
"... the shape of the cultural element is variable, but its claims in the culture war always revolve around providing a way of seeing the world and being in it." #NewRight

"The culture wars are, in fact, wars for the provisions that are achieved via the cultural content. A song, a video, an image, a painting, a book, a philosophical address, a pamphlet, a happening, a meme:..." #NewRight

"To Giovanni Sartori, this power is overwhelming, because it is the product of one of the most crucial revolutions: the revolution of mass communications. With this, mass media technology has definitely brought the "victory of the cannon". #NewRight

"Thus, it is feasible to determine, at last, the concrete type of power I was referring to when I talked about the power of mass communication: the power to produce and disseminate particular cultural contents to an audience virtually comprised of the whole society,..." #NewRight
"A mass medium doesn't enact laws, but it issues ideas, words, information, guidelines for conduct, role models, which stereotypes to reject, moral schemas, aesthetics, etc." #NewRight

"A power that only crushes, that only has strength to force the body, is certainly a weak and unstable power. In contrast, a power that is efficient is one that forces the mind. The stability of power depends on its acceptance, and it is built with words, not weapons." #NewRight

"If this is so, then it is noted that power must not be reduced to mere coercion or the threat of coercion. The fact that power is irreducible to its negative functions means that power not only knows how to say "no", but it also knows how to say "yes"." #NewRight

"Power serves to impose a will. The content of the will imposed by power must be understood in a broad sense: from a determined course of action to a concrete way of thinking. A may want B to do C; A may want B to think D, A may want B to perceive E, etcetera." #NewRight

"Max Weber is a good reference point on the topic: "Power signifies the probability that one actor within a social relationship will be in a position to carry out his own will despite resistance, regardless of the basis on which this probability rests"." #NewRight
